# The 1700s
# JUNE 14, 1775
The [Continental Congress](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) authorizes the creation of the Continental Army, and the next day, puts it under the command of George Washington. After the Revolution, it would be known as the [U.S. Army](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/Military-Units/Army/).
[ ![a revolutionary battle](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/1-jun1775.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/1-jun1775.jpg)
# OCTOBER 13, 1775
The Continental Congress votes to create the Continental Navy, which later becomes the [U.S. Navy](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/Military-Units/Navy/).
[ ![the continental navy](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/2-oct1775.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/2-oct1775.jpeg)
# NOVEMBER 10, 1775
The Second Continental Congress establishes the Continental Marines, predecessor of the [U.S. Marine Corps](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/Military-Units/Marine-Corps/).
[ ![the home of the continental marines](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/3-nov1775.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/3-nov1775.jpeg)
# JULY 4, 1776
The Second Continental Congress unanimously [adopts the Declaration of Independence](https://www.loc.gov/item/today-in-history/july-04/), announcing the colonies' separation from Britain.
[ ![congress signing the declaration of independence](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/4-jul1776-2.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/4-jul1776-2.jpg)
# SEPTEMBER 3, 1783
American and British delegations sign [Treaty of Paris](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/), ending the Revolutionary War and recognizing the United States as an independent nation.
[ ![a painting of the treaty of paris signing](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/5-sep1783-2.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/5-sep1783-2.jpg)
# AUGUST 7, 1789
Congress [establishes the War Department](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) at the cabinet level to oversee the operation and maintenance of the [Army, Navy and Marine Corps](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Quizzes/Quiz/Article/2041448/military-units-how-is-each-service-organized/).
# AUGUST 4, 1790
Congress Congress establishes the Revenue Cutter Service, predecessor of today's [Coast Guard](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/).
[ ![a painting of the original coast guard](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/6-aug1790.png) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/6-aug1790.png)
# APRIL 30, 1798
The War Department transfers oversight of the Navy to the newly established [Navy Department](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/).
[ ![a painting of a battle at sea between the navy & france](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/7-april1798.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1700s-images/7-april1798.jpeg)
## The Continental Congress
The Continental Congress was the governing body by which the American colonial governments coordinated their resistance to British rule during the first two years of the American Revolution. The Congress balanced the interests of the different colonies and also established itself as the official colonial liaison to Great Britain. As the war progressed, the Congress became the effective national government of the country, and, as such, conducted diplomacy on behalf of the new United States.
[Learn More](https://history.state.gov/milestones/1776-1783/continental-congress)
## America Declares its Independence
The Declaration of Independence is adopted by the Second Continental Congress. Following a decade of agitation over taxes and a year of war, representatives make the break with Britain. King George III isn't willing to let his subjects go without a fight, and loyalist sentiment remains strong in many areas. Americans' primary allegiance is to their states; nationalism will grow slowly.
[Learn More](https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/creating-the-united-states/interactives/declaration-of-independence/overview.html)
## The Treaty of Paris
The American War for Independence (1775-1783) was actually a world conflict, involving not only the United States and Great Britain, but also France, Spain and the Netherlands. The peace process brought a nascent United States into the arena of international diplomacy, playing against the largest and most established powers on earth.
The three American negotiators – John Adams, Benjamin Franklin and John Jay – proved themselves ready for the world stage, achieving many of the objectives sought by the new United States. Two crucial provisions of the treaty were British recognition of U.S. independence and the delineation of boundaries that would allow for American western expansion.
[Learn More](https://www.archives.gov/milestone-documents/treaty-of-paris)
## The Establishment of the Department of War
On this date, President George Washington signed into law a bill that established the U.S. War Department. The measure had moved through the First Federal Congress (1789–1791) with relatively little controversy. With Jonathan Trumbull Jr. of Connecticut presiding over the Committee of the Whole, the House debated the authorization bill in late June 1789. Pro-Administration Representative Egbert Benson of New York introduced an amendment to include a phrase to the effect that the War Department secretary would be “removable by the president.” This echoes language that had been included in a much more rancorous debate a few days earlier about the duties and powers of the proposed secretary of foreign affairs (later the secretary of state). Roger Sherman of Connecticut and John Page of Virginia opposed Benson's amendment, but it carried narrowly, 24 to 22. The entire bill passed the House easily on June 27, 1789, with little debate in an unrecorded vote. Soon thereafter, the Senate passed the bill. In choosing the department's first secretary, President Washington preferred continuity. He nominated Henry Knox — a key aide during the American Revolution and, since 1785, the secretary of war under the Articles of Confederation.
[Learn More](https://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1700s/The-establishment-of-the-Department-of-War/)
## The Establishment of the Coast Guard
On Aug. 4, 1790, President George Washington signed legislation establishing a maritime force simply called “the cutters” or “the system of cutters.” Thus was born the United States Revenue Cutter Service, known today as the U.S. Coast Guard.
Congress empowered these cutters to enforce national laws, in particular those dealing with tariffs. This small fleet was the first U.S. naval force available to protect U.S. maritime interests in the early years of the new republic.
