# The 1800s
# MARCH 16, 1802
President Thomas Jefferson signed the Military Peace Establishment Act into law, creating the [U.S. Military Academy](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) at West Point, N.Y.
[ ![a group of soldier marching to the mess hall at west point](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/1-march1802.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/1-march1802.jpeg)
# JUNE 18, 1812
The United States declares war — what came to be known as the [War of 1812](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) — on Great Britain in response to British naval blockades and the forced conscription of American sailors into the Royal Navy.
[ ![a painting depicting a naval battle from the war of 1812](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/2-june1812.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/2-june1812.jpg)
# AUGUST 24, 1814
The War Department building is [set on fire](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) during the War of 1812. All books and records are saved, having been removed a few days earlier.
[ ![a comic depicting the burning of washington by the british](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/3-aug1814-3.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/3-aug1814-3.jpeg)
# FEBRUARY 17, 1815
President James Madison ratifies the [Treaty of Ghent](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/), officially ending the War of 1812.
[ ![a painting of the treat of ghent being ratified](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/4-feb1815.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/4-feb1815.jpg)
# JUNE 30, 1834
[The Marine Corps is transferred to the Department of the Navy](https://www.defense.gov/News/Feature-Stories/story/Article/1763150/why-are-marines-part-of-the-navy/).
[ ![an image of marines apart of the newly formed marine corps](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/5-june1834.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/5-june1834.jpeg)
# OCTOBER 10, 1845
The [Naval School](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/), a precursor to the U.S. Naval Academy, is established in Annapolis, Md.
[ ![an early photo of the Naval School](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/6-oct1845-2.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/6-oct1845-2.jpeg)
# MAY 13, 1846 - MARCH 10, 1848
[The United States and Mexico go to war](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) over a border dispute in Texas and President James K. Polk's broader ambitions to claim Mexican territories in what are now the states of California and New Mexico.
[ ![a painting depicting the U.S. dragoons from the mexican-american war](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/7-may1846-2.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/7-may1846-2.jpg)
# JULY 1, 1850
The Naval School officially becomes known as the [U.S. Naval Academy](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/).
[ ![a photo of students enrolled at the naval academy](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/8-july1850.jpeg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/8-july1850.jpeg)
# APRIL 12, 1861 - APRIL 9, 1865
[Civil War](https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Experience/The-History-of-the-Department-of-Defense/) is fought between the United States and the Confederate States of America, the 11 southern states that left the Union after President Abraham Lincoln's election. After the war, the United States readmitted the former Confederate states and abolished the institution of slavery. 
[ ![a comic depiciting america being torn apart by the civil war](https://www.defense.gov/portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/231116-D-D0439-100.jpg) ](https://www.defense.gov/Portals/1/Interactive/2023/11-historyofdod/1800s-images/231116-D-D0439-100.jpg)
